<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,151,792]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,658,683]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Comments.</emphasis>
Because of its small papillae, this species is inconspicuous and easily overlooked; even on fully illuminated substrata the papillae are hidden among algal turf. A closely related species (based on spicule morphology), 
<taxonomicName box="[314,459,730,755]" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" genus="Pione" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="lampa">
<emphasis box="[314,459,730,755]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Pione lampa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(de Laubenfels), first described from 
<collectingCountry box="[900,1003,730,755]" name="Bermuda" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
(as 
<taxonomicName box="[1055,1131,730,755]" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" genus="Cliona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1055,1131,730,755]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Cliona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), is encrusting (as well as excavating), bright vermillion in color, and only grows in full sunlight; it has not yet been reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[1324,1399,766,791]" name="Belize" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Belize</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
